postcontent: I do not really want to sell this AR, but the cash wouldn't hurt, and I received orders to Quantico for further training.  I have owned this rifle since I was 16 and have put lots of time, money, and effort into its upkeep and modification.  It is a DPMS Panther Arms Mod A-15 Sporticle (I was young. The hardware, optics, case, and ammunition are a large chunk of the value (over $800 brand new).  Everything is in perfect condition, with the exception of a few cosmetic scratches.  It has primarily served as a range and hunting weapon, and has seen a few 3-gun competitions.  Everything about the action is perfect, well-maintained, and clean.  I have never had it jam or misfire.  It would make a perfect starter AR, and I would recommend for anyone that wants an instantly ready and customizable AR.

title: For Sale:  Russian Tula Tokarev SVT 40 WWII
postcontent: Very nice Finnish Captured Tokarev 7.62x54Rmm Russian SVT 40 made back in 1941. The rifle still looks darn impressive for a 75 year old service rifle. The barrel is 26 3/4 inches to the end of the muzzle break. The bluing is in very nice condition and the bore is excellent with a shiny surface and sharp lands. The bolt has been refinished and has a nice bronze color finish. The front sight is a hooded post. The rear sight is a “U” notch blade assembly attached to a sliding elevator that is marked from 1 – 15. The magazine is a modern replacement. The LOP (Length of pull) measures 13 inches from the front of the trigger to the back of the butt plate. It comes with a stock butt plate. This type of rifle was featured on Season 1 Episode 1 of the History Channel’s Top Shot television show. The Tokarev SVT 40 rifle was used during the very first challenge the contestants were involved in. Here is a chance to own a piece of firearms history. The rifle was made during WWII by the Russians and was probably used to kill Nazis. Later it was captured by the Finnish Army during the Continuation War and was probably used to kill Russians. It was eventually imported to the United States where it was made a part of television history on the appropriately named History Channel... Mint rifle and don't miss you by. I would ship...
